@GRMIDX{{index="@HI{{toiu}}" grammar="@HI{{to @KJ{{say}}}}"}}

<body>

<h1>@HI{{to @KJ{{say}}}}</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li> @Splain{{}}@HI{{to@KJ{{say}}}}
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
To directly quote what someone says or has said, repeat their words exactly and follow with @HI{{to @KJ{{say}}}}.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{lie*down}}ru maeni [o@KJ{{rest}}minasai]to @KJ{{say}}imasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      We say "Good night" before we go to bed.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
To quote indirectly, use the plain form before @HI{{to @KJ{{say}}}}. The tense of the quoted text is 
unaffected by the tense of the main sentence.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KT{{mira-}}sanha @KJ{{come^week east^capital}}he @KJ{{exit^long}}suruto @KJ{{say}}imashita.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Mr. Miller said that he would go to Tokyo on a business trip next week.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
If it appears at the end of a sentence @HI{{to@KJ{{say}}}} indicates hearsay ("I heard that ...", "It is said that ...").
This form is most often used in written Japanese.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{zono@KJ{{environs}}riha,@KJ{{once*upon*a*time}},@KJ{{wide}}i@KJ{{plains^meadow}}datta<strong>toiu</strong.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Long ago, this neighbourhood used to be fields, I heard.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

